aterial practice, explaining why writing practices designed during the colonial era to isolate the government from society have become a means of participation in it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aBureaucracy -- Pakistan -- Islamabad. 0aBureaucracyzPakistanzIslāmābād. 0aBureaucracyzPakistanzIslāmābād. 0aCapitals (Cities) -- Pakistan -- Planning. 0aCapitals (Cities)zPakistanxPlanning. 0aCity planning -- Pakistan -- Islamabad. 0aCity planningzPakistanzIslāmābād. 0aCity planningzPakistanzIslāmābād. 0aGovernment paperwork -- Pakistan -- Islamabad. 0aGovernment paperworkzPakistanzIslāmābād. 0aGovernment paperworkzPakistanzIslāmābād. 0aIslamabad (Pakistan) -- Politics and government. 0aMunicipal government -- Pakistan -- Records and correspondence. 0aMunicipal governmentzPakistanvRecords and correspondence. 0aMunicipal governmentzPakistanxRecords and correspondence. 0aPublic records -- Pakistan -- Islamabad. 0aPublic recordszPakistanzIslāmābād. 0aPublic recordszPakistanzIslāmābād. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  abuilders.  abureaucracy.  abureaucratic documentation.  abureaucrats.  abusinessmen.  acolonial era.  acontemporary history.  aimams.  aislamabad.  alegal anthropology.  amaterial infrastructure.  amaterials.  amiddle east scholars.  amiddle east.  amodern pakistan.  anonfiction.  apakistan.  apaper artifacts.  apaper documents.  apaper mediation.  apolitical economy.  apoliticians.  apostcolonialism.  aproperty owners.  asocial science.  astate government.  aurban bureaucracy.  aurban landscape.  aurbanism.  avillagers.1 aArbor, Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversit